Properties
The notion of GŒ¥ sets in metric (and topological) spaces is related to the notion of completeness of the metric space as well as to the Baire category theorem.  See the result about completely metrizable spaces in the list of properties below.  
  
    
      
        
          
            G
            
              Œ¥
            
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \mathrm {G_{\delta }} }
   sets and their complements are also of importance in real analysis, especially measure theory.

Basic properties
The complement of a GŒ¥ set is an FœÉ set, and vice versa.
The intersection of countably many GŒ¥ sets is a GŒ¥ set.
The union of finitely many GŒ¥ sets is a GŒ¥ set.
A countable union of GŒ¥ sets (which would be called a GŒ¥œÉ set) is not a GŒ¥ set in general.  For example, the rational numbers 
  
    
      
        
          Q
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \mathbb {Q} }
   do not form a GŒ¥ set in 
  
    
      
        
          R
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \mathbb {R} }
  .
